\section{Project Description}

Our goal for this project is to use a Baxter robot to classify items into different categories depending on their shape and corresponding attributes.\medskip\\
First, we will have basic shapes like triangles, circles, and rectangles placed on a surface (our backup plan due to potential difficulties in precise classification is to mark the surface and/or item by an AR tag). Baxter will sense the items by using the camera attached to it to take a picture of the area it will scan. Since the possibility that the image will contain regions we do not want to focus on, we have to ensure those regions are removed. The image collected will serve as input for an algorithm that will apply image processing and edge detecting filters (ie: Canny Edge Detection, Gaussian blurring) in order to better detect the shapes. \smallskip\\Second, a template matching algorithm will take the a gray-scale version of the filtered image as a gray-scale version of the image and multiple templates for each of the shapes we want to sort through. The algorithm will detect the shapes on the surface and compute the centroid of corners with some threshold as target location.\smallskip\\Third, we can then apply inverse kinematics to control Baxter's gripper to go to the desired location and pick up the item. Safety issue could be raised by Baxter's arm damaging other items along the path to target. Each shape will have a final target location of where it is supposed to go to and Baxter will place it there.\medskip\\
The template matching algorithm can be adjusted to use multiple strategies to be able to detect the shapes. We were thinking about using fast, normalized cross-correlation to find instances of the templates in the image that Baxter takes. We would allow for multiple peaks to pass through, so we can take into consideration the case where there can be multiple shapes of the same kind. Another thing we can do is apply image filters (Gaussian blurring, bilateral filtering, etc..) to help the template matching algorithm get better results.\medskip\\
Implementing a basic classification model for Baxter can have many real life applications. One that stands out is using this type of system to find common, everyday life objects for people that are sightless or incapacitated. Other applications can include sorting packages in warehouses and organizing products in store shelves.

